<body>
    <h1 style="text-align:center;">Historic Cities of India</h1>
    
    <div class="city-container">
        <h2>Varanasi – The Eternal City</h2>
        <div class="image-container">
            <img src="/images/varanasi-1.jpeg">
            <img src="/images/varanasi-2.jpeg">
            <img src="/images/varanasi-3.jpeg">
        </div>
        <p>Varanasi, also known as Kashi, is one of the world’s oldest continuously inhabited cities, dating back over 3,000 years. Situated on the banks of the Ganges River, Varanasi has been a center for Hinduism, attracting sages, scholars, and devotees. The city is famous for its Ganga Ghats, where people perform religious rituals, and the mesmerizing Ganga Aarti held every evening. In ancient times, Varanasi was also a center for education, with scholars teaching Vedic scriptures, astronomy, and philosophy. The food culture here includes kachoris, rabri, and thandai, reflecting North Indian traditions. It is also known for its Banarasi silk sarees, woven by skilled artisans for centuries. Many believe that dying in Varanasi ensures liberation from the cycle of rebirth, making it a sacred pilgrimage site for Hindus.
        </p>
    </div>

    <div class="city-container">
        <h2>Jaipur – The Pink City</h2>
        <div class="image-container">
            <img src="/images/jaipur1.jpeg" alt="Hawa Mahal">
            <img src="/images/jaipur2.jpeg" alt="Amber Fort">
            <img src="/images/jaipur3.jpeg" alt="City Palace">
        </div>
        <p>Jaipur, the capital of Rajasthan, was founded in 1727 by Maharaja Sawai Jai Singh II. It was India’s first planned city, built according to Vastu Shastra, with wide streets and grand palaces. The Hawa Mahal, Amber Fort, and City Palace are prime examples of Rajput architecture, blending Hindu and Mughal styles. The lifestyle of ancient Jaipur was dominated by royalty, warriors, and artisans. The Rajput kings patronized art and culture, leading to the development of miniature paintings, blue pottery, and gemstone jewelry. The local cuisine includes dal baati churma, gatte ki sabzi, and laal maas, showcasing the flavors of Rajasthani heritage. Festivals like Teej and Gangaur are celebrated with processions and traditional dances, keeping the city’s culture alive.</p>    </div>

    <div class="city-container">
        <h2>Hampi – The Lost Empire</h2>
        <div class="image-container">
            <img src="/images/hampi1.jpeg" alt="Virupaksha Temple">
            <img src="/images/hampi2.jpeg" alt="Stone Chariot">
            <img src="/images/hampi3.jpeg" alt="Hampi Bazaar">
        </div>
        <p>Hampi, located in Karnataka, was once the grand capital of the Vijayanagara Empire in the 14th century. It was one of the wealthiest cities in the world, known for its magnificent temples, bustling markets, and advanced infrastructure. The Virupaksha Temple, Vittala Temple, and Lotus Mahal are some of its architectural wonders. The people of Hampi lived in well-planned settlements, and the city’s economy thrived on agriculture, textile production, and international trade. The food culture included millet-based dishes, rice, and coconut curries, influenced by South Indian traditions. Hampi was also a center for Carnatic music and classical dance, which flourished under royal patronage. In 1565, the city was invaded and destroyed by the Deccan Sultanates, leaving behind breathtaking ruins that continue to attract tourists and historians.</p>
    </div>
    
    <div class="city-container">
        <h2>Madurai – The Temple City</h2>
        <div class="image-container">
            <img src="/images/madurai1.jpeg" alt="Virupaksha Temple">
            <img src="/images/madurai2.jpeg" alt="Stone Chariot">
            <img src="/images/madurai3.jpeg" alt="Hampi Bazaar">
        </div>
        <p>Madurai, located in Tamil Nadu, is one of India’s oldest cities, with a history dating back over 2,500 years. It was ruled by the Pandya dynasty, which transformed it into a hub of Tamil literature, trade, and culture. The city is home to the Meenakshi Temple, a stunning example of Dravidian architecture, famous for its towering gopurams (entrance towers) adorned with thousands of colorful sculptures. The daily life of Madurai revolved around its temples, where people gathered for religious ceremonies, festivals, and classical dance performances. The local cuisine is dominated by idlis, dosas, and spicy Chettinad curries, reflecting Tamil culinary traditions. The city’s markets were filled with silk, spices, and traditional handicrafts, making it an important trade center in South India..</p>
    </div>
    <div class="city-container">
        <h2>Dwarka – The Kingdom of Krishna</h2>
        <div class="image-container">
            <img src="/images/dwarka1.jpeg" alt="Virupaksha Temple">
            <img src="/images/dwarka2.jpeg" alt="Stone Chariot">
            <img src="/images/dwarka3.jpeg" alt="Hampi Bazaar">
        </div>
        <p>Dwarka, located in Gujarat, is believed to be the legendary kingdom of Lord Krishna, mentioned in the Mahabharata. It was once a flourishing port city that engaged in maritime trade with Persia, Rome, and Africa. The Dwarkadhish Temple, dedicated to Krishna, stands as a symbol of the city’s ancient spiritual significance. The people of Dwarka were skilled traders and fishermen, and their diet included seafood, wheat, and dairy-based dishes. The city’s culture was deeply rooted in Vaishnavism, with grand festivals like Janmashtami celebrated with devotion. Archaeological discoveries suggest that an underwater city once existed near Dwarka, possibly the remains of Krishna’s fabled kingdom.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="city-container">
        <h2>Thanjavur – The Chola Capital</h2>
        <div class="image-container">
            <img src="/images/thanjavur1.jpeg" alt="Virupaksha Temple">
            <img src="/images/thanjavur2.jpeg" alt="Stone Chariot">
            <img src="/images/thanjavur3.jpeg" alt="Hampi Bazaar">
        </div>
        <p>Thanjavur, in Tamil Nadu, was the capital of the Chola dynasty, one of the greatest South Indian empires. It became a center of Dravidian architecture, Carnatic music, and bronze sculpture-making. The Brihadeeswarar Temple, built by Raja Raja Chola I, is a UNESCO World Heritage Site, showcasing the architectural brilliance of the Cholas. The people of Thanjavur were deeply involved in temple activities, and festivals were celebrated with grandeur. The city was also famous for its Tanjore paintings, a unique art form that used gold foil to create divine imagery. The cuisine included tamarind rice, coconut-based curries, and South Indian sweets, which are still popular today.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="city-container">
        <h2>Mysore – The City of Palaces</h2>
        <div class="image-container">
            <img src="/images/mysore1.jpeg" alt="Virupaksha Temple">
            <img src="/images/mysore2.jpeg" alt="Stone Chariot">
            <img src="/images/mysore3.jpeg" alt="Hampi Bazaar">
        </div>
        <p>Mysore, the cultural capital of Karnataka, was the seat of the Wodeyar dynasty and later Tipu Sultan. It was a city of grandeur, known for its royal palaces, silk weaving, and classical music traditions. The Mysore Palace, with its Indo-Saracenic architecture, remains a symbol of its royal past. The people of Mysore led an artistic and refined lifestyle, with a focus on painting, music, and literature. The cuisine of Mysore includes Mysore Pak (a famous sweet), dosas, and filter coffee, which are now enjoyed across India. The city is also famous for the Mysore Dasara festival, a grand celebration with elephants, processions, and cultural performances.</p>
    </div>
    
